3nt.title: Relation
3nt.text:
%%comment:
I do not want to be shortened. The motivation for this is that I would prefer that someone has the ability to learn everything they need to know about relations just by reading the popup summary.
%%

[summary: A **relation** is a [3jz set] of [tuple_mathematics tuples], all of which have the same [tuple_arity arity]. The inclusion of a tuple in a relation indicates that the components of the tuple are related. A set of $n$-tuples is called an $n$*-ary relation*. Sets of pairs are called binary relations, sets of triples are called ternary relations, etc.

Examples of binary relations include the equality relation on natural numbers $\{ (0,0), (1,1), (2,2), ... \}$ and the predecessor relation $\{ (0,1), (1,2), (2,3), ... \}$. When a symbol is used to denote a specific binary relation ($R$ is commonly used for this purpose),  that symbol can be used with infix notation to denote set membership: $xRy$ means that the pair $(x,y)$ is an element of the set $R$.]

A *relation* is a [3jz set] of [tuple_mathematics tuples], all of which have the same [todo: generalize the function_arity page to include general arity][tuple_arity arity]. The inclusion of a tuple in a relation indicates that the components of the tuple are related. A set of $n$-tuples is called an $n$*-ary relation*. Sets of pairs are called binary relations, sets of triples are called ternary relations, etc.

Examples of binary relations include the equality relation on natural numbers $\{ (0,0), (1,1), (2,2), ... \}$ and the predecessor relation $\{ (0,1), (1,2), (2,3), ... \}$. When a symbol is used to denote a specific binary relation ($R$ is commonly used for this purpose),  that symbol can be used with infix notation to denote set membership: $xRy$ means that the pair $(x,y)$ is an element of the set $R$.
